        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Lesson 1: Physiological Triggers
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="lesson-1" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <nav class="lesson-inline-nav" aria-label="Lesson navigation">
            <span class="lesson-inline-nav__current">Lesson 1 of 4</span>
            <a href="#lesson-2" class="lesson-inline-nav__link lesson-inline-nav__link--next">
              Lesson 2: Preparing the Body
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M3 8h10M9 4l4 4-4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
            </a>
          </nav>
          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h2>Lesson 1: How Animals "Know" When to Migrate</h2>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="lesson1-intro-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p class="section-intro">
            In Week 5 you learned <em>what</em> migration is and <em>why</em> it evolves. But how does
            an individual animal "decide" when to start? The answer isn't conscious decision-making —
            it's a cascade of <strong>physiological triggers</strong> that link environmental cues to
            internal hormonal changes, ultimately producing the urge to move. Understanding this
            cascade is where Level 3 Biology gets genuinely exciting — and it's the kind of
            mechanistic explanation that distinguishes Excellence from Merit.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>The Big Picture</h4>
            <p>
              Migration timing is controlled by an interaction between <strong>external cues</strong>
              (photoperiod, temperature) and an <strong>internal biological clock</strong> (circannual
              rhythm). The external cue acts as a <em>Zeitgeber</em> — a "time-giver" — that
              calibrates the internal clock. The clock then triggers a <strong>hormonal cascade</strong>
              that produces physiological and behavioural changes: fat deposition, muscle growth,
              organ remodelling, and ultimately <strong>Zugunruhe</strong> — migratory restlessness.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Photoperiod: The Master Cue ── -->
          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h3 id="photoperiod">Photoperiod: The Master Cue</h3>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="photoperiod-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            Of all the environmental signals that could trigger migration — temperature, rainfall,
            food availability — <strong>photoperiod</strong> (day length) is the most reliable.
            Unlike temperature, which fluctuates unpredictably, day length changes with mathematical
            precision every year. It is the one environmental variable that is guaranteed to be the
            same on the same date, year after year. Evolution has exploited this reliability.
          </p>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Exam Tip</h4>
            <p>
              A common error is stating that "animals migrate because it gets cold". Temperature is
              unreliable — a warm spell in autumn wouldn't delay migration indefinitely. Always
              identify <strong>photoperiod</strong> as the primary trigger and explain <em>why</em>
              it is more reliable than temperature: it is <strong>predictable</strong> and
              <strong>consistent between years</strong>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <h4>How is photoperiod detected?</h4>

          <p>
            The pathway from light detection to hormonal response is a multi-step signalling
            cascade. In birds (the best-studied migratory group), it works like this:
          </p>

          <div class="pathway-diagram fade-in-up">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 800 520" class="pathway-svg" role="img" aria-label="Photoperiod signalling pathway diagram showing the cascade from light detection in the retina through the hypothalamus to hormonal changes">
              <defs>
                <marker id="arrowhead" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="9" refY="3.5" orient="auto">
                  <polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)" opacity="0.8"/>
                </marker>
                <marker id="arrowhead-pink" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="9" refY="3.5" orient="auto">
                  <polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)" opacity="0.8"/>
                </marker>
                <marker id="arrowhead-green" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="9" refY="3.5" orient="auto">
                  <polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="var(--green-vivid)" opacity="0.8"/>
                </marker>
              </defs>

              <!-- Title -->
              <text x="400" y="30" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-primary)" font-size="16" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">Photoperiodic Signalling Cascade</text>

              <!-- Step 1: Light -->
              <rect x="30" y="55" width="160" height="75" rx="10" fill="none" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
              <text x="110" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)" font-size="13" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">LIGHT</text>
              <text x="110" y="98" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">Changing photoperiod</text>
              <text x="110" y="114" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">detected by retina</text>

              <!-- Arrow 1 -->
              <line x1="190" y1="92" x2="240" y2="92" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrowhead)" opacity="0.6"/>

              <!-- Step 2: SCN -->
              <rect x="250" y="55" width="180" height="75" rx="10" fill="none" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
              <text x="340" y="77" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)" font-size="13" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">SCN</text>
              <text x="340" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">Suprachiasmatic nucleus</text>
              <text x="340" y="111" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">(hypothalamus "clock")</text>

              <!-- Arrow 2 -->
              <line x1="430" y1="92" x2="480" y2="92" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrowhead)" opacity="0.6"/>

              <!-- Step 3: Pineal -->
              <rect x="490" y="55" width="160" height="75" rx="10" fill="none" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
              <text x="570" y="77" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)" font-size="13" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">PINEAL GLAND</text>
              <text x="570" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">Melatonin secretion</text>
              <text x="570" y="111" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">(high in dark, low in light)</text>

              <!-- Arrow down from Pineal -->
              <line x1="570" y1="130" x2="570" y2="170" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrowhead-pink)" opacity="0.6"/>

              <!-- Step 4: Hypothalamus GnRH -->
              <rect x="440" y="180" width="260" height="75" rx="10" fill="none" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
              <text x="570" y="202" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)" font-size="13" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">HYPOTHALAMUS</text>
              <text x="570" y="220" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">GnRH release → pituitary</text>
              <text x="570" y="236" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">(melatonin pattern decoded)</text>

              <!-- Arrow down to pituitary -->
              <line x1="570" y1="255" x2="570" y2="295" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrowhead-pink)" opacity="0.6"/>

              <!-- Step 5: Anterior Pituitary -->
              <rect x="440" y="305" width="260" height="75" rx="10" fill="none" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
              <text x="570" y="327" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--green-vivid)" font-size="13" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">ANTERIOR PITUITARY</text>
              <text x="570" y="345" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">LH + FSH secretion</text>
              <text x="570" y="361" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">(gonadotropins)</text>

              <!-- Arrows branching to gonads and adrenal -->
              <line x1="490" y1="380" x2="300" y2="420" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrowhead-green)" opacity="0.6"/>
              <line x1="650" y1="380" x2="700" y2="420" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrowhead-green)" opacity="0.6"/>

              <!-- Step 6a: Gonads -->
              <rect x="160" y="425" width="260" height="80" rx="10" fill="none" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
              <text x="290" y="447" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--green-vivid)" font-size="13" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">GONADS</text>
              <text x="290" y="465" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">Testosterone / oestrogen</text>
              <text x="290" y="481" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">→ gonadal growth, breeding readiness</text>
              <text x="290" y="497" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">→ Zugunruhe (migratory restlessness)</text>

              <!-- Step 6b: Adrenal / CORT -->
              <rect x="610" y="425" width="180" height="80" rx="10" fill="none" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
              <text x="700" y="447" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--green-vivid)" font-size="13" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">ADRENAL CORTEX</text>
              <text x="700" y="465" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">Corticosterone</text>
              <text x="700" y="481" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">→ fat mobilisation</text>
              <text x="700" y="497" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="11" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">→ hyperphagia</text>

              <!-- Side annotation: Deep brain photoreceptors -->
              <rect x="30" y="170" width="220" height="90" rx="10" fill="var(--surface-3)" stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.8"/>
              <text x="140" y="192" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--accent)" font-size="11" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">BIRDS ALSO HAVE:</text>
              <text x="140" y="210" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="10.5" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">Deep brain photoreceptors</text>
              <text x="140" y="226" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="10.5" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">(light passes through thin skull</text>
              <text x="140" y="242" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="10.5" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">directly to hypothalamus)</text>

              <!-- Dashed line from annotation to hypothalamus -->
              <line x1="250" y1="215" x2="440" y2="215" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4 3" opacity="0.4"/>
            </svg>
          </div>

          <p>
            This cascade has a beautiful logic: a <strong>predictable external signal</strong>
            (photoperiod) is transduced into an <strong>internal hormonal signal</strong> (melatonin
            pattern) that the hypothalamus "reads" to determine the time of year. The hypothalamus
            then activates the <strong>HPG axis</strong> (hypothalamic–pituitary–gonadal axis),
            which triggers the physiological changes needed for migration.
          </p>

          <div class="info-cards-row">
            <div class="info-card info-card--direction">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 40 40" fill="none">
                  <circle cx="20" cy="14" r="8" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.4"/>
                  <path d="M12 14h16" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.3"/>
                  <path d="M16 30v-12M24 30v-12" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.5"/>
                  <path d="M14 26h12" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.3"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Melatonin</h4>
              <p>
                Secreted by the pineal gland during <strong>darkness</strong>. Long nights = long
                melatonin signal. The <em>duration</em> of the melatonin pulse tells the hypothalamus
                what season it is.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--distance">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 40 40" fill="none">
                  <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="14" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.3"/>
                  <path d="M20 10v20M10 20h20" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.3"/>
                  <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="4" fill="var(--green-vivid)" opacity="0.3"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>GnRH</h4>
              <p>
                Gonadotropin-releasing hormone. Released in <strong>pulses</strong> from the
                hypothalamus. Pulse frequency and amplitude increase as day length reaches the
                <strong>critical photoperiod</strong>.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--quality">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 40 40" fill="none">
                  <rect x="8" y="12" width="24" height="16" rx="4" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.4"/>
                  <path d="M14 18v4M20 16v6M26 20v2" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.6"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Corticosterone</h4>
              <p>
                The main glucocorticoid stress hormone in birds. Elevated corticosterone
                <strong>mobilises fat reserves</strong>, increases foraging intensity, and triggers
                hyperphagia (excessive eating) in the pre-migratory period.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>


          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>Critical Photoperiod</h4>
            <p>
              Each species has a <strong>critical daylength</strong> — a specific number of
              hours of light per day that triggers the migratory cascade. This is not a gradual
              response; it's more like a <strong>threshold switch</strong>. When photoperiod crosses
              the threshold, the hormonal programme activates. This is why birds in the same
              population tend to depart within a tight window — they all hit the same photoperiodic
              threshold at the same time.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>Excellence link:</strong> The critical photoperiod is <em>genetically
              determined</em> and <em>locally adapted</em>. Populations of the same species at
              different latitudes may have different critical photoperiods — because the "correct"
              departure date depends on local conditions.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── The Hormonal Cascade ── -->
          <h3 id="hormones">The Hormonal Cascade: From Signal to Action</h3>

          <p>
            Once the photoperiodic threshold is crossed, the hypothalamus orchestrates a suite of
            hormonal changes that prepare the animal's body for the enormous physiological demands
            of migration. Think of it as a <strong>coordinated remodelling programme</strong> —
            the body literally rebuilds itself for a different mode of operation.
          </p>

          <div class="hormone-timeline fade-in-up">
            <div class="timeline-phase">
              <div class="timeline-marker timeline-marker--1"></div>
              <div class="timeline-content">
                <h4>Phase 1: Photoperiodic Activation</h4>
                <p class="timeline-timing">Weeks to months before departure</p>
                <p>
                  Decreasing melatonin duration (longer days) triggers hypothalamic GnRH release.
                  The HPG axis activates. Gonads begin to enlarge — in some species, testes increase
                  <strong>300–500×</strong> in mass. Testosterone and oestrogen levels rise.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="timeline-phase">
              <div class="timeline-marker timeline-marker--2"></div>
              <div class="timeline-content">
                <h4>Phase 2: Hyperphagia</h4>
                <p class="timeline-timing">2–4 weeks before departure</p>
                <p>
                  Rising corticosterone and prolactin trigger <strong>hyperphagia</strong> —
                  a dramatic increase in food intake. Birds may eat <strong>2–3× their normal daily
                  intake</strong>, rapidly depositing subcutaneous fat. The kuaka doubles its body
                  mass before departure, with fat comprising up to <strong>55% of total body mass</strong>.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="timeline-phase">
              <div class="timeline-marker timeline-marker--3"></div>
              <div class="timeline-content">
                <h4>Phase 3: Body Remodelling</h4>
                <p class="timeline-timing">Days to weeks before departure</p>
                <p>
                  The body undergoes remarkable structural changes:
                </p>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                  <li><strong>Pectoral muscle hypertrophy</strong> — flight muscles enlarge by 20–40% to power sustained flight</li>
                  <li><strong>Organ shrinkage</strong> — the gut, liver, and kidneys <em>atrophy</em> (shrink), reducing dead weight that isn't needed during non-stop flight</li>
                  <li><strong>Heart enlargement</strong> — cardiac output increases to meet the demands of sustained aerobic exercise</li>
                  <li><strong>Haemoglobin changes</strong> — some species shift to haemoglobin variants with higher oxygen affinity for high-altitude flight</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="timeline-phase">
              <div class="timeline-marker timeline-marker--4"></div>
              <div class="timeline-content">
                <h4>Phase 4: Zugunruhe</h4>
                <p class="timeline-timing">Immediately before departure</p>
                <p>
                  The final behavioural signal: <strong>Zugunruhe</strong> (German: "migration
                  restlessness"). The bird becomes intensely agitated, oriented in the migratory
                  direction, and attempts to fly — even in captivity. This marks the transition
                  from preparation to action.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="think-prompt fade-in-up">
            <h4>Think About It</h4>
            <p>
              Why would it be adaptive for an animal to <em>shrink</em> its digestive organs before
              migration? Consider the kuaka, which flies 12,000 km non-stop without eating. What is
              the cost of carrying a full-sized gut and intestines during that flight?
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Zugunruhe ── -->
          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h3 id="zugunruhe">Zugunruhe: Migratory Restlessness</h3>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="zugunruhe-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            <strong>Zugunruhe</strong> (pronounced <em>TSOOG-oon-roo-uh</em>) is one of the most
            fascinating phenomena in animal behaviour. It was first systematically studied using
            the <strong>Emlen funnel</strong> — a simple but elegant experimental apparatus.
          </p>

          <div class="experiment-card fade-in-up">
            <h4>The Emlen Funnel Experiment</h4>
            <div class="experiment-setup">
              <div class="experiment-desc">
                <p>
                  <strong>Stephen Emlen</strong> (1967) placed migratory birds in funnel-shaped
                  cages lined with ink-sensitive paper. As the bird hopped and fluttered, its inky
                  footprints recorded the <strong>direction</strong> of its attempted movement.
                </p>
                <h5>Key findings:</h5>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                  <li>During the migratory season, birds showed <strong>directional restlessness</strong> — footprints clustered in the compass direction of their normal migration route</li>
                  <li>Outside the migratory season, footprints were <strong>randomly distributed</strong> — no preferred direction</li>
                  <li>The duration of restlessness approximately matched the <strong>normal duration of migration</strong> for that species</li>
                  <li>Birds kept in <strong>constant conditions</strong> (artificial light cycle) still showed restlessness at the right time of year — evidence of an endogenous programme</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="funnel-diagram">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 240 260" class="funnel-svg" role="img" aria-label="Diagram of an Emlen funnel showing directional footprint clustering">
                  <!-- Funnel shape -->
                  <ellipse cx="120" cy="220" rx="100" ry="20" fill="none" stroke="var(--text-muted)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
