                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="summary-box">
            <h4>What Zugunruhe Proves</h4>
            <p>
              Zugunruhe demonstrates that migration is <strong>not simply a response to immediate
              environmental conditions</strong> (like cold weather or food shortage). It is driven
              by an <strong>endogenous programme</strong> — an internal biological clock that
              activates at the appropriate time of year, even in the absence of external cues.
              The programme encodes both the <strong>direction</strong> and approximate
              <strong>duration</strong> of migration.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Endogenous Clock vs External Cues ── -->
          <h3>The Endogenous Clock: Gwinner's Warblers</h3>

          <p>
            The most compelling evidence for an internal migratory clock comes from
            <strong>Eberhard Gwinner's</strong> classic experiments with European garden warblers
            (<em>Sylvia borin</em>) in the 1960s–1980s.
          </p>

          <div class="experiment-card fade-in-up">
            <h4>Gwinner's Constant-Condition Experiment</h4>
            <div class="experiment-desc">
              <p>
                Gwinner hand-raised garden warblers from the egg and kept them in
                <strong>completely constant conditions</strong> — 12 hours light : 12 hours dark,
                constant temperature, constant food availability. No seasonal cues at all.
              </p>
              <h5>Results:</h5>
              <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>The birds still showed <strong>annual cycles</strong> of fat deposition, moult, and Zugunruhe — on roughly the right schedule</li>
                <li>The cycles were not exactly 12 months — they "free-ran" at about <strong>10–11 months</strong>, gradually drifting out of phase with the real seasons</li>
                <li>This proves the clock is <strong>endogenous</strong> (internal) — but it needs photoperiod as a <em>Zeitgeber</em> to stay calibrated to the real calendar</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                <strong>Conclusion:</strong> Migration timing is controlled by a
                <strong>circannual rhythm</strong> — an approximately year-long internal clock.
                Photoperiod fine-tunes the clock to prevent it drifting. This is analogous to how
                a circadian rhythm (daily clock) free-runs at ~25 hours but is entrained to
                24 hours by the light–dark cycle.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="connection-box fade-in-up">
            <h4>Linking to Earlier Weeks</h4>
            <p>
              In <strong>Week 4</strong> you learned about the <strong>sun compass</strong> and how
              animals use a time-compensated internal clock to navigate. The circannual clock for
              migration timing and the circadian clock for sun-compass navigation are
              <strong>related systems</strong> — both involve the suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) in
              the hypothalamus. This is why disrupting the SCN can simultaneously disrupt both
              navigation ability and migration timing.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>Zeitgeber Concept — Excellence Level</h4>
            <p>
              A <strong>Zeitgeber</strong> (German: "time-giver") is an environmental cue that
              <em>synchronises</em> (entrains) a biological clock to the external world. For
              migration:
            </p>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li><strong>Primary Zeitgeber:</strong> Photoperiod — most reliable, used to calibrate the circannual clock</li>
              <li><strong>Secondary Zeitgebers:</strong> Temperature, food availability, social cues — can fine-tune departure date within the window set by photoperiod</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              An excellent exam answer distinguishes between the <strong>endogenous timer</strong>
              (the circannual clock) and the <strong>Zeitgeber</strong> (photoperiod) that calibrates
              it. The clock generates the approximate timing; the Zeitgeber makes it precise.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── NZ Case Studies ── -->
          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h3 id="nz-case-studies">Aotearoa Case Studies: Physiological Triggers in Action</h3>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="nz-cases-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            Let's apply this hormonal framework to the NZ species you met in Week 5. Each case
            illustrates different aspects of the photoperiod → hormone → behaviour cascade.
          </p>

          <!-- Kuaka case study -->
          <div class="case-study-card fade-in-up">
            <div class="case-study-card__header">
              <div class="case-study-card__species">
                <h4>Kuaka <span class="showcase-card__latin">(Bar-tailed Godwit)</span></h4>
                <span class="showcase-card__scientific"><em>Limosa lapponica baueri</em></span>
              </div>
              <span class="migration-badge migration-badge--seasonal">Seasonal</span>
            </div>
            <div class="case-study-card__body">
              <h5>Pre-migratory physiology</h5>
              <p>
                Kuaka undergo the most extreme pre-migratory body remodelling of any bird. In the
                weeks before their 12,000 km non-stop flight from NZ to Alaska:
              </p>
              <ul class="feature-list">
                <li><strong>Hyperphagia:</strong> Body mass nearly doubles — from ~250 g to ~450 g. Fat reserves reach 55% of body mass</li>
                <li><strong>Pectoral muscles:</strong> Enlarge by ~30% — hypertrophy of flight muscle fibres</li>
                <li><strong>Gut atrophy:</strong> The digestive tract shrinks by up to 25%. The bird won't eat for 8–9 days, so digestive organs become dead weight</li>
                <li><strong>Kidney and liver shrinkage:</strong> Non-essential metabolic organs reduced</li>
                <li><strong>Heart enlargement:</strong> Cardiac muscle increases to support sustained aerobic output</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="case-study-card__highlight">
                <h5>The Hormonal Picture</h5>
                <p>
                  Plasma <strong>corticosterone</strong> rises sharply 2–3 weeks before departure,
                  driving hyperphagia and fat mobilisation. <strong>Prolactin</strong> levels change
                  in concert. Gonadal hormones are suppressed during the southward (non-breeding)
                  migration but elevated during the northward (breeding) migration — a neat example
                  of how the same species can have different hormonal profiles for different
                  migratory legs.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="exam-tip">
                <h4>Excellence Tip</h4>
                <p>
                  At Excellence level, you need to <strong>link physiological changes to adaptive
                  advantage</strong>. Don't just describe what changes — explain <em>why</em> each
                  change improves survival. Gut shrinkage reduces mass → reduces energy cost of
                  flight → increases range. Muscle hypertrophy increases thrust → enables sustained
                  flight. Frame each change in terms of the cost–benefit analysis from Week 5.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Tuna case study -->
          <div class="case-study-card fade-in-up">
            <div class="case-study-card__header">
              <div class="case-study-card__species">
                <h4>Tuna <span class="showcase-card__latin">(Longfin Eel)</span></h4>
                <span class="showcase-card__scientific"><em>Anguilla dieffenbachii</em></span>
              </div>
              <span class="migration-badge migration-badge--breeding">Breeding</span>
            </div>
            <div class="case-study-card__body">
              <h5>The silver eel transformation</h5>
              <p>
                The longfin eel's pre-migratory transformation is arguably the most dramatic of
                any NZ species. After 20–100+ years as a sedentary freshwater animal, the eel
                undergoes a complete <strong>metamorphosis</strong> driven by hormonal changes:
              </p>
              <ul class="feature-list">
                <li><strong>Eye enlargement:</strong> Eyes increase in diameter by 2–3× and shift to deep-sea visual pigments — adapting from freshwater murk to the open ocean</li>
                <li><strong>Skin silvering:</strong> Melanophores and guanine crystals produce a silver belly and dark back — <strong>countershading</strong> for camouflage in open water</li>
                <li><strong>Pectoral fin broadening:</strong> Fins enlarge for oceanic swimming</li>
                <li><strong>Gut degeneration:</strong> The entire digestive tract atrophies — the eel will never eat again. All energy for the 3,000 km swim comes from stored fat</li>
                <li><strong>Gonad maturation:</strong> Gonads enlarge enormously, filling much of the body cavity with developing eggs or sperm</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="case-study-card__highlight">
                <h5>Hormonal Control</h5>
                <p>
                  The "silvering" transformation is triggered by a surge in <strong>gonadotropins
                  (LH and FSH)</strong> from the pituitary, which in turn is controlled by
                  <strong>GnRH</strong> from the hypothalamus. The process also involves
                  <strong>thyroid hormones</strong> (T3/T4) and <strong>cortisol</strong> (the
                  mammalian/fish equivalent of corticosterone). Interestingly, in captive eels,
                  silvering can be artificially induced by injecting GnRH or LH — confirming
                  the hormonal control mechanism.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="connection-box">
                <h4>Link to Week 3</h4>
                <p>
                  In Week 3 you studied the glass eel's <strong>positive rheotaxis</strong> —
                  swimming against the current to reach freshwater. The silver eel's downstream
                  migration represents a complete <strong>reversal</strong> of this behaviour.
                  The switch from positive to negative rheotaxis is hormonally mediated —
                  another example of how hormones can fundamentally alter an animal's behavioural
                  response to the same stimulus.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Tītī case study -->
          <div class="case-study-card fade-in-up">
            <div class="case-study-card__header">
              <div class="case-study-card__species">
                <h4>Tītī <span class="showcase-card__latin">(Sooty Shearwater)</span></h4>
                <span class="showcase-card__scientific"><em>Ardenna grisea</em></span>
              </div>
              <span class="migration-badge migration-badge--seasonal">Seasonal</span>
            </div>
            <div class="case-study-card__body">
              <h5>Circannual clock precision</h5>
              <p>
                Tītī breed on islands around southern NZ (particularly the Tītī Islands near
                Rakiura/Stewart Island), then undertake a <strong>65,000 km figure-8 loop</strong>
                around the Pacific. The timing of departure is remarkably precise — most birds
                leave their breeding colonies within a <strong>2-week window</strong> each year.
              </p>
              <p>
                This precision points to a strong <strong>circannual clock</strong> entrained by
                photoperiod. Tītī experience dramatic changes in day length between their NZ
                breeding colonies (46°S) and their non-breeding range in the North Pacific (40–60°N).
                The shift from long southern-hemisphere summer days to the approaching equinox
                appears to trigger pre-migratory physiological changes including increased
                <strong>corticosterone</strong> and fat deposition.
              </p>

              <div class="case-study-card__highlight">
                <h5>Mātauranga Māori</h5>
                <p>
                  Ngāi Tahu muttonbirders have observed tītī migration timing for centuries.
                  Traditional knowledge records that tītī depart around <strong>late April–May</strong>
                  and return in <strong>September–October</strong>. This traditional ecological
                  knowledge aligns precisely with modern satellite-tracking data — a powerful example
                  of how long-term cultural observation can generate accurate biological knowledge
                  independent of Western scientific methodology.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Extension: Scholarship Level ── -->
          <h3>Scholarship Extension: Epigenetics and Migratory Flexibility</h3>

          <div class="scholarship-extension fade-in-up">
            <p>
              The framework above — photoperiod → hormones → migration — explains the core
              mechanism well. But it raises a deeper question: if migration timing is genetically
              programmed, how can populations <strong>adapt rapidly</strong> to changing conditions
              (e.g. climate change shifting the optimal departure date)?
            </p>
            <p>
              Recent research has revealed that <strong>epigenetic mechanisms</strong> may play
              a crucial role. Epigenetic modifications — changes to gene expression that don't
              alter the DNA sequence itself — can be influenced by environmental conditions and,
              in some cases, transmitted across generations.
            </p>

            <h4>Key evidence:</h4>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                <strong>DNA methylation patterns</strong> in migratory bird populations differ
                from those in resident (non-migratory) populations of the same species — even when
                the underlying DNA sequences are identical. This suggests epigenetic "switches"
                that can activate or suppress the migratory programme.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Blackcap warblers</strong> (<em>Sylvia atricapilla</em>) in central Europe
                have evolved a new migratory direction (northwest to Britain instead of southwest to
                Africa) in just ~50 years — far too fast for conventional genetic change. Epigenetic
                regulation of clock genes may facilitate this rapid behavioural shift.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Partial migration</strong> — where some individuals in a population migrate
                and others don't — may be regulated epigenetically. The "decision" to migrate could
                depend on early-life conditions (maternal stress, nutrition) that set epigenetic
                marks on migration-related genes.
              </li>
            </ul>

            <div class="exam-tip">
              <h4>Scholarship Tip</h4>
              <p>
                At Scholarship level, you're expected to <strong>integrate across biological
                levels</strong>. A top answer would link molecular mechanisms (DNA methylation,
                histone modification) → gene expression (clock genes, hormone receptor genes) →
                physiological changes (HPG axis activation) → behaviour (Zugunruhe, departure
                timing) → ecological consequences (population-level migration patterns) →
                evolutionary implications (rapid adaptation to climate change).
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

        </section><!-- /lesson-1 -->


