          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h2>Lesson 3: How Did Migration Evolve?</h2>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="lesson3-intro-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p class="section-intro">
            In Lessons 1 and 2 you learned <em>how</em> migration is triggered and <em>how</em> the body
            prepares for it. But that raises a deeper question: <strong>how did something this complex
            evolve in the first place?</strong> A kuaka doesn't just fly 12,000 km — it rebuilds its
            entire body first, navigates with pinpoint accuracy, and arrives at a specific estuary in
            New Zealand. How does evolution produce a behaviour this elaborate?
          </p>

          <p>
            The answer lies in understanding that migration didn't appear overnight. It evolved
            <strong>gradually</strong>, through small changes over millions of years — and we can see
            that evolutionary process still happening today in species where <strong>some individuals
            migrate and others don't</strong>. These "partial migrants" give us a living window into
            how migration evolves.
          </p>

          <div class="connection-box fade-in-up">
            <h4>Building on Level 2 Biology</h4>
            <p>
              This lesson connects directly to concepts you learned in Level 2. In
              <strong>AS 91157 (Genetic Variation and Change)</strong> you studied natural selection,
              allele frequency, gene pools, genetic drift, and gene flow. In
              <strong>AS 91159 (Gene Expression)</strong> you learned how genes are expressed as
              proteins and how environment influences phenotype. We're now applying all of that
              to a real-world question: how does natural selection shape a complex behaviour
              like migration?
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── The Big Question ── -->
          <h3>Where Did Migration Come From?</h3>

          <p>
            There are two competing hypotheses about how bird migration originated, and the answer
            matters because it tells us whether migration was always "built in" to birds or whether
            it evolved from scratch.
          </p>

          <div class="info-cards-row">
            <div class="info-card info-card--direction">
              <h4>Northern Home Hypothesis</h4>
              <p>
                Birds originally lived year-round in <strong>temperate regions</strong>. As ice ages
                made winters harsher, some individuals began moving south in autumn to survive —
                and those that did had higher fitness. Over time, natural selection extended these
                seasonal movements into full migration.
              </p>
              <p class="info-card__evidence">
                <strong>Evidence:</strong> Recent genomic analysis of the largest radiation of
                migratory songbirds in the Americas (emberizoid passerines) supports this —
                migration evolved primarily through shifts of <em>winter</em> ranges toward the
                tropics from ancestral temperate breeding grounds (Winger et al. 2014).
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--distance">
              <h4>Southern Home Hypothesis</h4>
              <p>
                Birds originally lived in the <strong>tropics</strong>. As some individuals ventured
                north to breed — where food was abundant and competition lower during summer — they
                returned south for winter. Natural selection favoured this pattern because tropical
                "home" populations faced intense competition, while temperate summers offered
                a breeding bonanza.
              </p>
              <p class="info-card__evidence">
                <strong>Evidence:</strong> Some lineages (e.g. New World orioles) do appear to
                have followed this path, but recent evidence suggests it's less common than
                previously thought.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>The Gradualist Theory</h4>
            <p>
              Both hypotheses share a core insight: migration evolved through
              <strong>gradual extension of smaller annual movements</strong>. A bird that moved
              50 km to find food in winter had slightly higher survival than one that didn't.
              Its offspring inherited the tendency. Over thousands of generations, that 50 km
              became 500, then 5,000, then 12,000.
            </p>
            <p>
              This is natural selection acting on <strong>heritable variation in movement
              behaviour</strong> — exactly the mechanism you learned in Level 2 AS 91157.
              The key difference is that instead of acting on a visible trait like colour,
              selection is acting on a <em>behavioural</em> trait encoded by multiple genes.
            </p>
          </div>


          <div class="experiment-card fade-in-up">
            <h4>Evidence: The Northern Wheatear's Fossil Route</h4>
            <div class="experiment-desc">
              <p>
                The <strong>northern wheatear</strong> (<em>Oenanthe oenanthe</em>) provides
                striking evidence that migratory routes persist long after the conditions that
                created them have changed.
              </p>
              <p>
                Originally a Eurasian species, wheatears colonised North America as ice sheets
                retreated around <strong>20,000 years ago</strong>. But here's the remarkable thing —
                none of these North American wheatears winter in the Americas. They <em>all</em>
                still retrace their ancestral migratory paths back to wintering grounds in
                <strong>Africa</strong>, flying either east across the Atlantic or west across Asia.
              </p>
              <p>
                This demonstrates <strong>evolutionary inertia</strong> — the migratory programme
                is so deeply encoded in their genes that it persists even when the geographical
                context has completely changed.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="think-prompt fade-in-up">
            <h4>Think About It</h4>
            <p>
              Over the last 2.5 million years, Earth has experienced more than
              <strong>20 glacial cycles</strong> — ice sheets advancing and retreating. How might
              these repeated cycles have acted as a "pump" that reinforced migratory behaviour?
              Think about what happens to bird populations when ice sheets push them south, then
              retreat and allow recolonisation northward.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Partial Migration ── -->
          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h3 id="partial-migration">Partial Migration: A Window Into Evolution</h3>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="partial-migration-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            If migration evolves gradually, then we should be able to find species that are
            "partway there" — populations where <strong>some individuals migrate and others don't</strong>.
            And that's exactly what we find. It's called <strong>partial migration</strong>, and it's
            arguably the most common form of migration in the animal kingdom.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>What Is Partial Migration?</h4>
            <p>
              A partially migratory population contains <strong>both migratory and resident
              individuals</strong>. Not all members migrate — some stay put year-round. This is
              different from full migration (where everyone migrates) and residency (where nobody does).
            </p>
            <p>
              In Australia, <strong>44% of non-passerine birds</strong> and <strong>32% of passerine
              species</strong> are partially migratory. It's far more widespread than most people realise.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p>
            Why would partial migration be so common? Because it represents a
            <strong>bet-hedging strategy</strong>. If the winter is mild, residents do well — they
            don't waste energy migrating and they get first pick of territories in spring. But if
            the winter is harsh, migrants survive because they've moved to better conditions. By
            having both strategies in the same population, the species hedges its bets against
            environmental unpredictability.
          </p>

          <h4>What determines whether an individual migrates?</h4>

          <p>
            Whether an individual in a partially migratory population migrates is influenced by
            a combination of factors — and this is where your Level 2 genetics becomes important:
          </p>

          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li>
              <strong>Genetics</strong> — there is a heritable propensity to migrate. Some individuals
              are genetically "programmed" to migrate more than others. This is the raw material
              for natural selection.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Body condition</strong> — in some species, lighter juveniles are more likely
              to migrate (they can't compete for winter food with heavier birds). Remember from
              Level 2: <em>phenotype = genotype + environment</em>.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Age and sex</strong> — juveniles and females often migrate more frequently than
              dominant adults and males.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Social status</strong> — dominant individuals may be able to remain resident
              (holding the best territories year-round), while subordinates are "pushed out" into migration.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Exam Tip: Phenotype = Genotype + Environment</h4>
            <p>
              This is a perfect place to use the Level 2 equation. In partial migration,
              the <strong>genotype</strong> determines the individual's threshold for migration
              (some birds have a lower threshold, making them more likely to migrate). The
              <strong>environment</strong> (food availability, winter severity, competition)
              determines whether that threshold is crossed. Two birds with the same genotype
              might show different behaviours in different years. This interaction between
              genes and environment is exactly what AS 91159 prepared you for.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Berthold's Blackcap Experiments ── -->
          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h3 id="blackcap-experiments">Berthold's Blackcap Experiments: Proof That Migration Is Genetic</h3>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="blackcap-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            The most important experiments on the genetics of migration were conducted by
            <strong>Peter Berthold</strong> and colleagues at the Max Planck Institute for
            Ornithology, using the <strong>European blackcap</strong> (<em>Sylvia atricapilla</em>).
            These experiments are exam favourites because they demonstrate, with elegant simplicity,
            that migratory behaviour has a strong genetic basis.
          </p>

          <div class="experiment-card fade-in-up">
            <h4>Experiment 1: Selective Breeding — Can You Breed Migration In and Out?</h4>
            <div class="experiment-desc">
              <p>
                Berthold started with a <strong>partially migratory population</strong> from
                southern France — approximately <strong>75% migrants, 25% residents</strong>.
              </p>
              <p>
                He then conducted a two-way selective breeding experiment with
                <strong>458 birds</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>One line was selectively bred for <strong>migratoriness</strong> — only the most migratory birds were allowed to breed</li>
                <li>The other line was selectively bred for <strong>sedentariness</strong> — only the most sedentary birds bred</li>
              </ul>
              <h5>Results:</h5>
              <p>
                Within <strong>3–6 generations</strong>, Berthold achieved populations that were
                <strong>almost completely migratory or almost completely sedentary</strong>.
              </p>
              <p>
                The <strong>heritability</strong> of migratory activity was estimated at
                <strong>0.37–0.46</strong> (where 0 means entirely environmental and 1 means
                entirely genetic). This is a strong heritability — comparable to human height.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="connection-box fade-in-up">
            <h4>Connecting to Level 2: Allele Frequency</h4>
            <p>
              What Berthold did is exactly what you studied in AS 91157 — <strong>directional
              selection</strong> changing <strong>allele frequencies</strong> in a population.
              By only allowing migratory birds to breed, he increased the frequency of
              "migration alleles" in the gene pool. By only allowing sedentary birds to breed,
              he decreased them. The fact that this worked so quickly tells us that the genetic
              variation was already present in the population — selection just shifted which
              alleles were most common.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="experiment-card fade-in-up">
            <h4>Experiment 2: Cross-Breeding — Is Direction Genetic Too?</h4>
            <div class="experiment-desc">
              <p>
                German blackcaps migrate <strong>south-west</strong> to Spain and North Africa.
                Austrian blackcaps migrate <strong>south-east</strong> to the eastern Mediterranean.
              </p>
              <p>
                Berthold crossed them. The <strong>F1 hybrid offspring showed an intermediate
                migratory direction</strong> — south, splitting the difference between south-west
                and south-east.
              </p>
              <p>
                This proved that <strong>migratory direction is also genetically controlled</strong>
                — not learned from parents, not determined by experience, but encoded in the
                bird's DNA.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="experiment-card fade-in-up">
            <h4>Experiment 3: Cross-Breeding Migrants with Non-Migrants</h4>
            <div class="experiment-desc">
              <p>
                Migratory German blackcaps were crossed with <strong>non-migratory Cape Verde
                Islands blackcaps</strong> (an island population that never migrates).
              </p>
              <p>
                Result: about <strong>40% of F1 hybrids developed migratory activity</strong>.
                This tells us migration is not controlled by a single gene — it's a
                <strong>polygenic trait</strong> (controlled by multiple genes). This is consistent
                with Berthold's <strong>threshold model</strong>: many genes each contribute a small
                amount, and whether an individual migrates depends on whether the total genetic
                "score" crosses a threshold.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Interactive: Berthold's Threshold Model -->
          <div class="threshold-model fade-in-up">
            <h4>Berthold's Threshold Model</h4>
            <div class="threshold-diagram">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 700 240" class="threshold-svg" role="img" aria-label="Diagram showing Berthold's polygenic threshold model for migration. A bell curve of genetic scores, with a threshold line separating migrants from residents.">
                <defs>
                  <linearGradient id="bellGrad" x1="0" y1="0" x2="1" y2="0">
                    <stop offset="0%" stop-color="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stop-opacity="0.2"/>
                    <stop offset="50%" stop-color="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stop-opacity="0.5"/>
                    <stop offset="100%" stop-color="var(--green-vivid)" stop-opacity="0.5"/>
                  </linearGradient>
                </defs>

                <!-- Axes -->
                <line x1="60" y1="190" x2="640" y2="190" stroke="var(--text-muted)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <line x1="60" y1="30" x2="60" y2="190" stroke="var(--text-muted)" stroke-width="1.5"/>

                <!-- X-axis label -->
                <text x="350" y="225" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="12" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">Genetic "migration score" (sum of many gene effects)</text>

                <!-- Y-axis label -->
                <text x="20" y="110" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="12" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif" transform="rotate(-90 20 110)">Frequency</text>

                <!-- Bell curve (approximate normal distribution) -->
                <path d="M80,188 C120,186 160,175 200,150 C240,120 280,70 330,45 C360,35 390,35 420,55 C460,80 500,130 540,160 C570,175 600,185 620,188"
                      fill="url(#bellGrad)" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.8"/>

                <!-- Threshold line -->
                <line x1="420" y1="25" x2="420" y2="195" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="6 3"/>
                <text x="420" y="18" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)" font-size="12" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">THRESHOLD</text>

                <!-- Labels for regions -->
                <text x="230" y="205" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)" font-size="11" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">RESIDENTS</text>
                <text x="230" y="218" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">(below threshold)</text>

                <text x="540" y="205" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--green-vivid)" font-size="11" font-weight="600" font-family="'Space Grotesk', sans-serif">MIGRANTS</text>
                <text x="540" y="218" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="'Inter', sans-serif">(above threshold)</text>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <p>
              Think of it like exam marks: each gene contributes a few "points" to a migration
              score. If your total score crosses the threshold, you migrate. If not, you stay.
              This explains why a partially migratory population has some migrants and some
              residents — individuals near the threshold can go either way depending on
              environmental conditions. <strong>Selection can shift the whole curve</strong>
              left (more residents) or right (more migrants) by changing allele frequencies
              — which is exactly what Berthold demonstrated.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Evolution in Real Time ── -->
          <h3>Evolution in Real Time: The Blackcap's New Migration Route</h3>

          <p>
            Here's where the blackcap story gets truly extraordinary — it provides evidence of
            <strong>evolution happening right now, in a timescale we can observe</strong>.
          </p>

          <div class="case-study-card fade-in-up">
            <div class="case-study-card__header">
              <div class="case-study-card__species">
                <h4>The British-Wintering Blackcaps</h4>
                <span class="showcase-card__scientific"><em>Sylvia atricapilla</em></span>
              </div>
              <span class="migration-badge migration-badge--seasonal">Evolving Now</span>
            </div>
            <div class="case-study-card__body">
              <p>
                Traditionally, Central European blackcaps wintered in <strong>Spain and North
                Africa</strong> (south-west). But starting in the 1960s — when backyard bird
                feeding became popular in Britain — some blackcaps began wintering in
                <strong>Britain</strong> instead (north-west).
              </p>

              <h5>What's happened in ~30 generations:</h5>
              <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>
                  Approximately <strong>10%</strong> of the Central European population now
                  winters in Britain
                </li>
                <li>
                  British-wintering blackcaps have evolved <strong>rounder wings</strong>
                  (better manoeuvrability for shorter flights) compared to the
                  <strong>pointier wings</strong> of Spanish-winterers (more efficient for
                  long-distance flight)
                </li>
                <li>
                  They've evolved <strong>narrower, longer beaks</strong> — suited to seeds
                  and suet from feeders — vs. the <strong>broader beaks</strong> of
                  Mediterranean-winterers, suited to fruit
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Reproductive isolation is developing:</strong> British-winterers arrive
                  at breeding grounds earlier (shorter journey), so they tend to mate with each
                  other rather than with later-arriving Spanish-winterers. This positive feedback
                  loop is increasing genetic divergence between the two groups
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="exam-tip">
                <h4>Exam Tip: Potential Speciation</h4>
                <p>
                  This is a textbook example of <strong>incipient speciation</strong> —
                  the early stages of one species splitting into two. Different selection
                  pressures (British vs. Mediterranean winters) + assortative mating (early
                  arrivals mate with early arrivals) = increasing genetic divergence. If you're
                  asked about how migration can drive speciation, this is your go-to example.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Migration Genes ── -->
          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h3 id="migration-genes">The Genetics of Migration: Candidate Genes</h3>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="migration-genes-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            If migration is genetic, which genes are involved? This is cutting-edge research —
            scientists are still mapping the full genetic architecture. But several candidate
            genes have been identified, and they connect beautifully to what you learned about
            gene expression in Level 2 (AS 91159).
          </p>

          <div class="info-cards-row">
            <div class="info-card info-card--direction">
              <h4>CLOCK Gene</h4>
              <p>
                Controls <strong>circadian rhythms</strong> — the daily internal clock. Variation
                in the number of poly-Q repeats (a short DNA sequence repeated different numbers
                of times) is associated with <strong>migration timing</strong>. More repeats =
                later spring migration in some species.
              </p>
              <p class="info-card__evidence">
                In the NZ <strong>silvereye (tauhou)</strong>, migrant individuals had longer
                CLOCK alleles than resident individuals in the same partially migratory population.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--distance">
              <h4>ADCYAP1 Gene</h4>
              <p>
                Codes for a <strong>neuropeptide</strong> involved in stress response and activity
                levels. Variation in this gene's regulatory region is associated with
                <strong>migratory restlessness</strong> (Zugunruhe). This single gene explains
                about <strong>3%</strong> of phenotypic variation in migratoriness.
              </p>
              <p class="info-card__evidence">
                That 3% may sound small, but remember — migration is <em>polygenic</em>.
                Many genes each contribute a small effect.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--quality">
              <h4>Willow Warbler: 2 Loci = 74%</h4>
              <p>
                A 2023 study found that in the willow warbler, just <strong>two genetic loci</strong>
                explain <strong>74%</strong> of the variation in migration direction. One involves
                a chromosome inversion; the other involves a transposable element cluster.
              </p>
              <p class="info-card__evidence">
                Most hybrids migrate like one parent (not intermediate) — so they don't suffer
                the cost of an inferior route.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="connection-box fade-in-up">
            <h4>Connecting to Level 2: Gene → Protein → Phenotype</h4>
            <p>
              In AS 91159 you learned the pathway: <strong>DNA → mRNA → protein →
              phenotype</strong>. The CLOCK gene produces a protein that regulates circadian
              rhythm. A change in the DNA sequence (a mutation — remember those from AS 91157?)
              changes the protein, which changes the circadian rhythm, which changes when the
              bird migrates. This is gene expression producing a <em>behavioural</em> phenotype
              — exactly the same mechanism as sickle cell producing a <em>structural</em>
              phenotype, just applied to the nervous system rather than haemoglobin.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>The "Migratory Gene Package" Hypothesis</h4>
            <p>
              Some researchers argue that <strong>the genetic framework for migration exists
              in nearly all bird species</strong> — even sedentary ones. The genes for
              navigation, fat storage, muscle remodelling, and Zugunruhe are all present;
              they just need to be "switched on" by the right combination of alleles and
              environmental conditions.
            </p>
            <p>
              This would explain why migratory behaviour can appear remarkably quickly in
              evolutionary terms — as it did after the last ice age, around 15,000 years ago.
              The genes were already there; natural selection simply shifted which alleles were
              most common, crossing the threshold from resident to migrant.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── NZ Evolutionary Case Studies ── -->
          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h3 id="nz-evolution">Aotearoa Evolutionary Case Studies</h3>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="nz-evolution-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            Let's bring this back to New Zealand with three species that illustrate different
            aspects of migration's evolution.
          </p>

          <div class="case-study-card fade-in-up">
            <div class="case-study-card__header">
              <div class="case-study-card__species">
                <h4>Tauhou <span class="showcase-card__latin">(Silvereye)</span></h4>
                <span class="showcase-card__scientific"><em>Zosterops lateralis</em></span>
              </div>
              <span class="migration-badge migration-badge--seasonal">Partial Migrant</span>
            </div>
            <div class="case-study-card__body">
              <p>
                The silvereye self-introduced to New Zealand around <strong>1856</strong> — it flew
                across the Tasman from Australia and established itself without any human help.
                The Tasmanian subspecies is a <strong>partial migrant</strong>: most of the
                Tasmanian population crosses Bass Strait to mainland Australia each winter, but
                more northerly populations are resident year-round.
              </p>
              <p>
                Research across <strong>20 South Pacific silvereye populations</strong> found
                that in the partially migratory population, <strong>migrants had longer
                microsatellite alleles at the CLOCK gene</strong> than residents from the
                same population. This is direct evidence linking a specific gene to migratory
                behaviour within a partially migratory population — exactly the kind of
                variation that natural selection could act on.
              </p>
              <div class="exam-tip">
                <h4>Excellence Link</h4>
                <p>
                  The silvereye beautifully illustrates the connection between
                  <strong>gene → protein → behaviour → fitness → allele frequency change</strong>.
                  CLOCK gene variation produces different circadian proteins → different migration
                  timing → different survival in different environments → natural selection shifts
                  allele frequencies. That's the full Level 2 → Level 3 chain.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="case-study-card fade-in-up">
            <div class="case-study-card__header">
              <div class="case-study-card__species">
                <h4>Pīpīwharauroa <span class="showcase-card__latin">(Shining Cuckoo)</span></h4>
                <span class="showcase-card__scientific"><em>Chrysococcyx lucidus</em></span>
              </div>
              <span class="migration-badge migration-badge--seasonal">Full Migrant</span>
            </div>
            <div class="case-study-card__body">
              <p>
                This summer migrant breeds in New Zealand and winters in the Bismarck
                Archipelago and Solomon Islands. What makes it extraordinary for understanding
                the genetics of migration is this: young cuckoos are <strong>raised by grey
                warbler foster parents</strong> (the shining cuckoo is a brood parasite).
              </p>
              <p>
                Adults migrate north in February–March. The juveniles, raised by non-migratory
                warblers, migrate <strong>several months later</strong> — in April–May — having
                <em>never seen an adult of their own species migrate</em>. They navigate to
                the correct wintering grounds entirely on their own.
              </p>
              <p>
                This proves that the migratory route is <strong>genetically encoded, not
                learned</strong>. The cuckoo's migration programme — direction, distance, timing —
                is hardwired into its DNA. No learning. No cultural transmission. Pure genetics.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="case-study-card fade-in-up">
            <div class="case-study-card__header">
              <div class="case-study-card__species">
                <h4>Kuaka <span class="showcase-card__latin">(Bar-tailed Godwit)</span></h4>
                <span class="showcase-card__scientific"><em>Limosa lapponica baueri</em></span>
              </div>
              <span class="migration-badge migration-badge--seasonal">Full Migrant</span>
            </div>
            <div class="case-study-card__body">
              <p>
                In 2022, a five-month-old juvenile kuaka (designated "B6") flew
                <strong>over 13,500 km</strong> from Alaska to Tasmania in 11 days — a new
                distance record. This was its very first migration. It had never made the
                journey before.
              </p>
              <p>
                Like the cuckoo, this demonstrates that the navigation programme, the
                physiological preparation, and the migratory restlessness are all
                <strong>genetically inherited</strong>. But unlike a cuckoo, the juvenile
                kuaka did have adults around it — so there may be some social facilitation
                in timing, even if the route itself is innate.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Video Resources ── -->
          <h3>Video Resources</h3>

