          <!-- ── Summary ── -->
          <div class="summary-box fade-in-up">
            <h4>Lesson 3 Summary</h4>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                Migration evolved <strong>gradually</strong> through small extensions of
                seasonal movements, driven by natural selection acting on heritable variation
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Partial migration</strong> — where both migrants and residents coexist
                in one population — is a living window into the evolutionary process
              </li>
              <li>
                Berthold's blackcap experiments proved migration is <strong>heritable</strong>
                (h² ≈ 0.4), <strong>polygenic</strong>, and can be altered by selection in
                just <strong>3–6 generations</strong>
              </li>
              <li>
                Both migratory <strong>propensity</strong> and <strong>direction</strong> are
                genetically controlled
              </li>
              <li>
                Candidate genes (CLOCK, ADCYAP1) link to circadian rhythm and migratory
                restlessness — connecting <strong>DNA → protein → behaviour</strong>
              </li>
              <li>
                NZ examples: the silvereye (CLOCK gene variation in partial migrants), the
                shining cuckoo (innate navigation without parental guidance), and juvenile
                kuaka (first-time navigation over 13,500 km)
              </li>
              <li>
                The blackcap's new British migration route shows evolution and potential
                <strong>speciation happening in real time</strong>
              </li>
            </ul>
