          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h2>Lesson 4: How Humans Are Disrupting Migration</h2>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="lesson4-intro-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p class="section-intro">
            You've now researched human impacts on migration yourselves. In this lesson we'll pull
            your findings together with the biology from Lessons 1–3 to understand <em>why</em>
            these impacts are so devastating — and why many migratory species may not be able to
            adapt fast enough to survive them.
          </p>

          <p>
            The core problem is this: migration is a finely tuned system. Triggers, preparation,
            navigation, stopover sites, breeding timing — every link in the chain has been shaped
            by natural selection over thousands of generations. Humans are now changing the
            environment faster than evolution can respond. Let's examine how.
          </p>


          <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
               Climate Change
               ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h3 id="climate-change">Climate Change: Disrupting Every Link in the Chain</h3>

          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h4>Phenological Mismatch — When Timing Falls Apart</h4>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="mismatch-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            In Lesson 1 you learned that migration timing is driven by <strong>photoperiod</strong> —
            an utterly reliable cue that has not changed. But the conditions photoperiod
            <em>predicts</em> have shifted. Spring arrives earlier, snow melts sooner, insects
            emerge weeks ahead of schedule — yet the bird in New Zealand or Africa still receives
            the same day-length signal it always did. It departs on time by its internal clock,
            but arrives <strong>late</strong> relative to the food peak.
          </p>

          <p>
            This is <strong>phenological mismatch</strong> — a decoupling of the environmental
            cue from the conditions it evolved to predict.
          </p>

          <!-- Red Knot Cascade Diagram -->
          <div class="cascade-diagram fade-in-up">
            <h4>Case Study: The Red Knot Cascade</h4>
            <p class="cascade-intro">
              The red knot (<em>Calidris canutus</em>) breeds in Arctic Russia and winters in
              West Africa — a round trip of over 30,000 km. A 2016 study in <em>Science</em>
              revealed a devastating chain reaction triggered by warming:
            </p>
            <div class="cascade-steps">
              <div class="cascade-step">
                <div class="cascade-step__number">1</div>
                <div class="cascade-step__content">
                  <strong>Arctic warming</strong> — Snowmelt in Arctic Russia is occurring ~0.5 days
                  earlier per year
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="cascade-arrow">
                <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none"><path d="M12 5v14M5 12l7 7 7-7" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
              </div>
              <div class="cascade-step">
                <div class="cascade-step__number">2</div>
                <div class="cascade-step__content">
                  <strong>Earlier insect peak</strong> — Insects emerge weeks before chicks hatch
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="cascade-arrow">
                <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none"><path d="M12 5v14M5 12l7 7 7-7" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
              </div>
              <div class="cascade-step">
                <div class="cascade-step__number">3</div>
                <div class="cascade-step__content">
                  <strong>Undernourished chicks</strong> — Born after the food peak, chicks grow
                  smaller with <strong>~15% shorter bills</strong> than birds from the 1980s
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="cascade-arrow">
                <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none"><path d="M12 5v14M5 12l7 7 7-7" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
              </div>
              <div class="cascade-step">
                <div class="cascade-step__number">4</div>
                <div class="cascade-step__content">
                  <strong>Reduced fitness 15,000 km away</strong> — Short-billed birds in West Africa
                  can't reach deep-buried bivalves, must eat low-energy seagrass instead
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="cascade-arrow">
                <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none"><path d="M12 5v14M5 12l7 7 7-7" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
              </div>
              <div class="cascade-step cascade-step--final">
                <div class="cascade-step__number">5</div>
                <div class="cascade-step__content">
                  <strong>Lower survival</strong> — Population decline driven by events on the
                  breeding ground affecting fitness on the wintering ground
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="exam-tip fade-in-up">
              <strong>Exam link:</strong> This is a perfect example of how an environmental change
              at one point in a migration route can have consequences thousands of kilometres away.
              The biology connects: photoperiod cue → hormonal cascade → departure timing →
              mismatch → developmental impact → fitness cost.
            </div>
          </div>


          <h4>Range Shifts</h4>
          <p>
            As temperatures rise, species track their thermal niche by moving
            <strong>poleward</strong> or to <strong>higher altitudes</strong>. Breeding ranges
            shift north; wintering ranges may shift too. But range boundaries can't always keep
            pace — species at the tops of mountains or at the poles have nowhere left to go. The
            result is a "squeeze" where suitable habitat shrinks from both ends.
          </p>


