          <!-- Sea Level Rise -->
          <div class="key-concept fade-in-up" style="margin-top: var(--space-6)">
            <h4>Sea Level Rise and Coastal Squeeze</h4>
            <p>
              Global mean sea level rise has <strong>more than doubled</strong> in 30 years — from
              2.1 mm/year in 1993 to approximately 4.5 mm/year in 2024. This is drowning the
              intertidal mudflats, salt marshes and sandy beaches that migratory species depend on
              for feeding and nesting.
            </p>
            <p>
              The problem is compounded by <strong>coastal squeeze</strong>: as the sea rises on one
              side, human development (roads, seawalls, buildings) prevents habitat from migrating
              inland. Coastal habitats are trapped between a rising ocean and a concrete wall.
            </p>
            <div class="stat-highlight">
              <span class="stat-highlight__number">97%</span>
              <span class="stat-highlight__text">projected loss of coastal wetlands by 2100 under high-emission scenarios</span>
            </div>
          </div>


