              <p class="info-card__text">New Zealand has lost 90% of its pre-European wetlands to agriculture and development</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            The longfin eel is now classified as <strong>At Risk — Declining</strong>. This is
            particularly devastating because eels are <em>semelparous</em> — they breed only once,
            then die. Every adult killed by a turbine represents 60–80 years of growth and the
            entire reproductive output of that individual, lost.
          </p>


          <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
               Light Pollution
               ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h3 id="light-pollution">Light Pollution: Hijacking Navigation</h3>

          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h4>ALAN — Artificial Light At Night</h4>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="light-pollution-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            Most migratory birds in the Northern Hemisphere migrate at <strong>night</strong>,
            navigating by the stars and the Earth's magnetic field. Artificial light disrupts both
            mechanisms. Bright lights attract nocturnal migrants like a porch light attracts moths —
            birds become trapped, circling buildings until they exhaust themselves or collide with
            glass. In the US alone, building collisions kill up to <strong>1 billion birds per year</strong>.
          </p>

          <p>
            A landmark 2017 study showed that a single high-intensity light installation — the
            Tribute in Light memorial in New York — trapped hundreds of migrating birds per hour
            on nights it operated. Turning the lights off for just 20-minute intervals allowed the
            birds to resume their migration.
          </p>

          <!-- Sea Turtle Hatchling Animation -->
          <h4>Sea Turtle Hatchlings: Following the Wrong Light</h4>

          <p>
            Sea turtle hatchlings emerge from nests at night and instinctively move toward the
            <strong>brightest horizon</strong>. In a natural environment, the open ocean reflects
            starlight and moonlight — brighter than the dark, vegetated dune behind them. Coastal
            lighting reverses this gradient, drawing hatchlings toward roads, hotels and
            streetlights instead of the sea.
          </p>

