          <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
               Why Can't They Adapt?
               ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h3 id="adaptation-limits">Why Can't They Adapt?</h3>

          <div class="section-header-with-audio">
            <h4>The Evolutionary Speed Limit</h4>
            <button class="audio-btn" id="adaptation-audio" title="Listen to Dr Eliot explain this">&#9654;</button>
          </div>

          <p>
            In Lesson 3 you learned that migration can evolve surprisingly fast — Berthold's
            blackcaps changed migratory direction in just 3–6 generations. So why can't today's
            migrants simply evolve to cope? The answer comes down to four key constraints:
          </p>

          <!-- Rate of Change Comparison -->
          <div class="rate-comparison fade-in-up">
            <h4>1. Rate of Change vs Evolutionary Time</h4>
            <p>
              Evolution requires heritable variation + selection + <em>time</em>. The post-glacial
              warming at the end of the last ice age occurred at roughly <strong>1°C per
              millennium</strong>. Current warming is occurring at roughly <strong>1°C per
              century</strong> — approximately <strong>10 times faster</strong>.
            </p>
            <div class="rate-bars">
              <div class="rate-bar">
                <div class="rate-bar__label">Post-glacial warming</div>
                <div class="rate-bar__track">
                  <div class="rate-bar__fill rate-bar__fill--slow" id="rate-bar-slow">
                    <span class="rate-bar__value">~1°C / 1,000 years</span>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="rate-bar__note">Species could track and adapt</div>
              </div>
              <div class="rate-bar">
                <div class="rate-bar__label">Current warming</div>
                <div class="rate-bar__track">
                  <div class="rate-bar__fill rate-bar__fill--fast" id="rate-bar-fast">
                    <span class="rate-bar__value">~1°C / 100 years</span>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="rate-bar__note">10× faster — outpacing evolution</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- The Photoperiod Trap -->
          <div class="key-concept fade-in-up">
            <h4>2. The Photoperiod Trap</h4>
            <p>
              This is the most fundamental constraint. Remember from Lesson 1: most migrants use
              <strong>day length</strong> as the master cue for departure. Photoperiod is a
              rock-solid proxy for time of year — it doesn't vary with weather.
            </p>
            <p>
              The problem: <strong>photoperiod has not changed</strong>. A kuaka in New Zealand in
              March experiences exactly the same day length as a kuaka in March 50 years ago. But
              the conditions at its Alaskan breeding ground <em>have</em> changed — snow melts
              earlier, insects peak earlier. The bird's departure cue (unchanged) no longer
              predicts the conditions it will encounter (shifted).
            </p>

            <!-- Photoperiod Trap Diagram -->
            <div class="photoperiod-trap-diagram">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 600 200" class="trap-svg" aria-label="Photoperiod trap diagram">
                <!-- Timeline -->
                <line x1="50" y1="100" x2="550" y2="100" stroke="var(--border-subtle)" stroke-width="1"/>
                <!-- Month labels -->
                <text x="100" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-body)">Mar</text>
                <text x="200" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-body)">Apr</text>
                <text x="300" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-body)">May</text>
                <text x="400" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-body)">Jun</text>
                <text x="500" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-muted)" font-size="10" font-family="var(--font-body)">Jul</text>
                <!-- Photoperiod cue (unchanged) -->
                <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="6" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)"/>
                <text x="200" y="85" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)" font-size="10" font-weight="600" font-family="var(--font-display)">Departure cue</text>
                <text x="200" y="75" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-cyan)" font-size="9" font-family="var(--font-body)">(same day length)</text>
                <!-- Old food peak -->
                <circle cx="400" cy="100" r="6" fill="var(--green-vivid)" opacity="0.4"/>
                <text x="400" y="145" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--green-vivid)" font-size="9" font-family="var(--font-body)" opacity="0.5">Old food peak</text>
                <!-- New food peak (shifted earlier) -->
                <circle cx="320" cy="100" r="6" fill="var(--green-vivid)"/>
                <text x="320" y="85" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--green-vivid)" font-size="10" font-weight="600" font-family="var(--font-display)">New food peak</text>
                <text x="320" y="75" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--green-vivid)" font-size="9" font-family="var(--font-body)">(shifted 2–3 weeks earlier)</text>
                <!-- Bird arrival (still on old schedule) -->
                <circle cx="400" cy="100" r="6" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)"/>
                <text x="400" y="165" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)" font-size="10" font-weight="600" font-family="var(--font-display)">Bird arrives</text>
                <text x="400" y="177" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)" font-size="9" font-family="var(--font-body)">(on old schedule)</text>
                <!-- Mismatch gap -->
                <line x1="325" y1="55" x2="395" y2="55" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="4 3"/>
                <text x="360" y="50" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--fluoro-pink)" font-size="10" font-weight="700" font-family="var(--font-display)">MISMATCH</text>
                <!-- Arrow showing shift -->
                <path d="M395,98 L330,98" fill="none" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#shift-arrow)"/>
                <defs>
                  <marker id="shift-arrow" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" refX="5" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M6,0 L0,3 L6,6" fill="var(--green-vivid)"/></marker>
                </defs>
              </svg>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Genetic Constraints -->
          <div class="key-concept fade-in-up">
            <h4>3. Genetic Constraints — Limited Raw Material</h4>
            <p>
              Natural selection can only work on existing genetic variation. Research shows that
              many migratory species have <strong>low polymorphism</strong> (genetic diversity) at
              the <strong>CLOCK gene locus</strong> — the very gene that helps control migration
              timing.
            </p>
            <p>
              Low diversity = little material for selection to act on. You can't select for earlier
              migration if all individuals carry essentially the same timing genotype. As one study
              concluded: <em>"low polymorphism at CLOCK may entail small potential for adaptive
              evolutionary response under climate change."</em>
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Population Bottlenecks -->
          <div class="key-concept fade-in-up">
            <h4>4. Population Bottlenecks</h4>
            <p>
              Many migratory species have already been driven to small populations by habitat loss,
              hunting and other pressures. Small populations have <strong>reduced genetic
              diversity</strong> through genetic drift and inbreeding — which means reduced
              evolutionary potential.
            </p>
            <p>
              The kuaka (bar-tailed godwit), with an estimated population of just ~41,500 mature
              individuals, is a prime example. A small population facing rapid environmental
              change has limited capacity to evolve its way out of trouble.
            </p>

            <div class="exam-tip fade-in-up">
              <strong>Exam link:</strong> This directly connects to Level 2 genetics (AS 91157).
              You can discuss allele frequency, gene pools, genetic drift in small populations,
              and the loss of alleles that might have conferred earlier migration timing. The
              biology at every level connects: DNA → protein → behaviour → fitness → population
              → species survival.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Summary ── -->
          <div class="summary-box fade-in-up">
            <h4>Lesson 4 Summary</h4>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                <strong>Climate change</strong> causes phenological mismatch — environmental cues
                (photoperiod) no longer predict the conditions migrants encounter at their
                destination
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Polar ice loss</strong> has two distinct stories: Arctic sea ice (already
                floating, minimal sea level impact) and Antarctic land ice (adds new water, the
                primary driver of sea level rise at ~150 Gt/year)
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Habitat destruction</strong> — especially at critical stopover sites like the
                Yellow Sea — breaks the migration chain. Dams block fish migration (longfin eel) and
                90% of NZ's wetlands have been drained
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Light pollution (ALAN)</strong> hijacks navigation systems — birds crash into
                lit buildings, sea turtle hatchlings follow the wrong horizon
              </li>
              <li>
                Additional threats include <strong>wind turbines</strong> (barotrauma in bats),
                <strong>overfishing</strong>, <strong>pesticides</strong> (neonicotinoids and
                monarchs), <strong>shipping noise</strong>, and <strong>invasive predators</strong>
              </li>
              <li>
                Animals struggle to adapt because the rate of environmental change
                <strong>outpaces evolution</strong> (~10× faster than post-glacial warming), the
                photoperiod cue hasn't changed, genetic diversity at timing loci is low, and small
                populations have limited evolutionary potential
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <nav class="lesson-inline-nav lesson-inline-nav--bottom" aria-label="Lesson navigation">
